mine the importance of religious diversity in the nation’s cultural, political, and economic life. He explores how religious language has given the United States some of its most enduring symbols and inspired its most vital civic institutions—and demonstrates how the genius of the American experiment lies in its empowerment of all people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCultural pluralismzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aAlasdair MacIntyre.  aAmerican Dream.  aAmerican civil religion.  aAmericans.  aAnne Hutchinson.  aArabs.  aBarack Obama.  aBigotry.  aBlack people.  aBuddhism.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholicism.  aChaplain.  aChristian amendment.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aCity on a Hill.  aCivil religion.  aCivil society.  aClergy.  aConfirmation bias.  aCulture of the United States.  aDaniel Kahneman.  aDissenter.  aDoctrine.  aDonald Trump.  aEstablishment Clause.  aFour Chaplains.  aFrank Gaffney.  aFreedom of religion.  aHatred.  aHindu.  aIdeology.  aIllustration.  aImmigration policy.  aImmigration.  aInstitution.  aInterfaith dialogue.  aIslam in the United States.  aIslam.  aIslamic Society of North America.  aIslamic culture.  aIslamic extremism.  aIslamophobia.  aJews.  aJihadism.  aJohn F. Kennedy.  aJohn Rawls.  aJohn Winthrop.  aJudaism.  aJudeo-Christian.  aLaurie Patton (Internet executive).  aLegislation.  aMartin Luther King, Jr.  aMinority religion.  aMosque.  aMuhammad.  aMulticulturalism.  aMuslim social.  aMuslim world.  aMuslim.  aNarrative.  aNational symbol.  aNew Testament.  aNew York University.  aNonbeliever.  aPolitical science.  aPrejudice.  aProtestantism.  aPublic reason.  aPublic sphere.  aPur